          Understanding Addiction as a Brain Disease
        </h2>
        <p class="mb-6 leading-relaxed">
          Addiction is a complex brain disorder that affects millions of people worldwide. 
          Despite common misconceptions that addiction results solely from poor choices or 
          moral failings, scientific evidence clearly shows that addiction is a chronic 
          brain disease that changes both brain structure and function. These changes can 
          be long-lasting and can lead to the harmful behaviors seen in people who 
          struggle with substance use disorders.
        </p>
        <p class="mb-8 leading-relaxed">
          This article explores the neuroscience of addiction, helping to dispel myths and 
          foster understanding of how substances affect the brain, why some people are 
          more vulnerable to addiction than others, and the implications for treatment and 
          recovery.
        </p>

        <!-- How Addiction Works Section -->
        <h2
          class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4 border-b-2 border-blue-500 pb-2"
        >
          How Addiction Works in the Brain
        </h2>
        <p class="mb-6 leading-relaxed">
          At its core, addiction involves the brain's reward system, a complex network of neural 
          circuits that evolved to motivate behaviors necessary for survival, such as eating 
          and reproducing. This system operates primarily through a neurotransmitter called 
          dopamine, which creates feelings of pleasure and reinforces behaviors.
        </p>
        <p class="mb-4 font-medium text-gray-700">The cycle of addiction typically involves three stages:</p>
        <ul class="list-disc list-inside mb-8 space-y-2">
          <li class="leading-relaxed">
            <strong class="font-semibold text-blue-600">Binge/Intoxication Stage</strong>
            - The individual takes an increasing amount of the substance, experiencing its rewarding or pleasurable effects
          </li>
          <li class="leading-relaxed">
            <strong class="font-semibold text-blue-600">Withdrawal/Negative Affect Stage</strong>
            - When the substance wears off, the individual experiences negative emotions and physical symptoms
          </li>
          <li class="leading-relaxed">
            <strong class="font-semibold text-blue-600">Preoccupation/Anticipation Stage</strong>
            - The individual becomes preoccupied with obtaining and using the substance again
          </li>
        </ul>

        <!-- The Dopamine Connection -->
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">
          The Dopamine Connection
        </h3>
        <p class="mb-4 leading-relaxed">
          Drugs of abuse cause a surge in dopamine that is much larger than what's triggered by natural 
          rewards. This flood of dopamine signals to the brain that something extremely important has happened 
          and should be remembered. The brain then begins to associate the drug with this strong reward 
          signal, driving continued use despite negative consequences.
        </p>
        <p class="mb-8 leading-relaxed">
          Over time, repeated exposure to the substance leads to tolerance—the individual needs more 
          of the substance to achieve the same effect. This occurs because the brain adapts to the consistently 
          high levels of dopamine by producing less of it or reducing the number of dopamine receptors.
        </p>

