          Why Some People Become Addicted and Others Don't
        </h2>
        <p class="mb-6 leading-relaxed">
          Addiction vulnerability varies significantly between individuals. The risk factors that contribute 
          to addiction can be grouped into three main categories:
        </p>

        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">
          1. Genetic Factors
        </h3>
        <p class="mb-4 leading-relaxed">
          Genetic factors account for approximately 40-60% of a person's vulnerability to addiction. 
          These genetic factors can influence:
        </p>
        <ul class="list-disc list-inside mb-8 space-y-2">
          <li class="leading-relaxed">How a person's body metabolizes substances</li>
          <li class="leading-relaxed">The intensity of pleasure or reward a person experiences from substances</li>
          <li class="leading-relaxed">Impulsivity and risk-taking tendencies</li>
          <li class="leading-relaxed">Vulnerability to mental health disorders that often co-occur with addiction</li>
        </ul>

        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">
          2. Environmental Factors
        </h3>
        <p class="mb-4 leading-relaxed">
          A person's environment also plays a crucial role in addiction vulnerability:
        </p>
        <ul class="list-disc list-inside mb-8 space-y-2">
          <li class="leading-relaxed">Exposure to trauma, especially during childhood</li>
          <li class="leading-relaxed">High levels of stress</li>
          <li class="leading-relaxed">Peer pressure and social influences</li>
          <li class="leading-relaxed">Availability and access to substances</li>
          <li class="leading-relaxed">Family attitudes toward substance use</li>
        </ul>

        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">
          3. Developmental Factors
        </h3>
        <p class="mb-4 leading-relaxed">
          The age at which a person begins using substances significantly impacts addiction risk:
        </p>
        <ul class="list-disc list-inside mb-8 space-y-2">
          <li class="leading-relaxed">
            The adolescent brain is particularly vulnerable as it's still developing, especially the 
            prefrontal cortex responsible for decision-making and impulse control
          </li>
          <li class="leading-relaxed">
            Early substance use can disrupt normal brain development and increase the likelihood of 
            developing an addiction later in life
          </li>
        </ul>

        <!-- Important Note Section -->
        <div
          class="my-8 border-l-4 border-yellow-500 pl-6 py-2 bg-yellow-50 rounded-lg shadow-sm"
        >
          <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-yellow-800 mb-2">Important Note</h3>
          <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
            Having risk factors for addiction doesn't guarantee that a person will develop an 
            addiction, just as the absence of risk factors doesn't ensure immunity. Addiction 
            results from complex interactions between genes, environment, and individual development.
          </p>
        </div>

        <!-- Implications for Treatment Section -->
