          Implications for Treatment and Recovery
        </h2>
        <p class="mb-6 leading-relaxed">
          Understanding addiction as a brain disease has profound implications for treatment approaches. 
          Effective addiction treatment typically involves:
        </p>

        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">
          Evidence-Based Approaches
        </h3>
        <ul class="list-disc list-inside mb-8 space-y-2">
          <li class="leading-relaxed">
            <strong class="font-semibold text-blue-600">Behavioral therapies</strong> - 
            Cognitive-behavioral therapy (CBT), motivational enhancement therapy, and 
            contingency management help address the psychological aspects of addiction
          </li>
          <li class="leading-relaxed">
            <strong class="font-semibold text-blue-600">Medications</strong> - 
            FDA-approved medications can help manage withdrawal symptoms, reduce cravings, 
            and treat co-occurring mental health disorders
          </li>
          <li class="leading-relaxed">
            <strong class="font-semibold text-blue-600">Comprehensive approach</strong> - 
            The most effective treatment addresses medical, psychological, social, vocational, 
            and legal problems in addition to substance use
          </li>
        </ul>

        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">
          Long-Term Recovery Perspective
        </h3>
        <p class="mb-4 leading-relaxed">
          Like other chronic diseases such as diabetes or hypertension, addiction often requires 
          long-term management:
        </p>
        <ul class="list-disc list-inside mb-8 space-y-2">
          <li class="leading-relaxed">
            Recovery is often a lifelong process with potential relapses that should be 
            viewed as opportunities for treatment adjustment, not as failures
          </li>
          <li class="leading-relaxed">
            Support systems, including family involvement and peer support groups, 
            play a crucial role in long-term recovery
          </li>
          <li class="leading-relaxed">
            Addressing co-occurring mental health disorders is essential for successful 
            addiction treatment
          </li>
        </ul>

        <!-- Conclusion Section -->
        <h2
